    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "idk, it just feels like such a dramatized way to describe physics. like, if it's just particles behaving in a way we didn't expect, why use a word like \"spooky\"? it almost makes it sound like there's something hidden or supernatural going on behind the scenes that we just can't see.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand your perspective. The term \"spooky\" did come from Einstein himself, and indeed, it might come off as dramatic or having an implication of something hidden or mystical. However, in the scientific community, it's taken quite literally, with physicists uniting under the term as a sort of geeky nod to one of the most famous quotations related to quantum mechanics. The term doesn't imply a hidden, supernatural cause; rather, it conveys the puzzlement at the strange and non-intuitive nature of quantum mechanics, which was very much a reality back then and still holds up to today's understanding. It's just that sometimes scientific discoveries present us with new realities that challenge our classical intuition, and labeling them as \"spooky\" was Einstein's honest admission of being mystified by the implications.",
      "source": "target",
